mutations <- read.csv("Lung_mutation_061621.csv")

names(mutations)[c(15, 19)] <- c("SNV_sensitivity", "INDEL_sensitivity")
names(mutations)[c(13, 17)] <- c("SNV_observed", "INDEL_observed")
names(mutations)[c(14, 18)] <- c("SNV_surveyed_genome", "INDEL_surveyed_genome")
names(mutations)[8] <- "Quit_years"
names(mutations)[11] <- "ULD"
names(mutations)[12] <- "CancerType"

mutations$Smoking_group <- factor(mutations$Smoking_group, levels = c("Never", "Light", 
    "Moderate", "Heavy"))

mutations$SNV_perCell.a <- mutations$SNV_perCell * mutations$SNV_sensitivity
mutations$INDEL_perCell.a <- mutations$INDEL_perCell * mutations$INDEL_sensitivity

SNV

1. Run negstive binomial regression model, using negative binomial for overdispersion

merge the individual, offset by coverage * sensitivity

2. Run Mixed Effect Negative Binomial model, with Individual as random effects

Among never smokers, show that age is correlated with mutation rate

library(MASS)
library(lme4)

observed <- aggregate(SNV_observed ~ Individual, mutations, sum)
surveyed_genome <- aggregate(SNV_surveyed_genome ~ Individual, mutations, sum)[, 
    2]
surveyed_genome_adjusted <- aggregate(I(SNV_surveyed_genome * SNV_sensitivity) ~ 
    Individual, mutations, sum)[, 2]

SNV <- data.frame(observed, surveyed_genome, surveyed_genome_adjusted)
SNV <- data.frame(SNV, mutations[match(SNV[, 1], mutations[, 2]), c(3:12)])

glm.fit0 <- glm.nb(SNV_observed ~ offset(log(surveyed_genome_adjusted)), subset = Smoking_status == 
    "Never_smoking", data = SNV)
glm.fit1 <- glm.nb(SNV_observed ~ Age + offset(log(surveyed_genome_adjusted)), subset = Smoking_status == 
    "Never_smoking", data = SNV)

Mutation rate among smokers are 53% higher than non-smokers, after adjusted for age, P-value = 0.016, there is no evidence for smoking*age interaction (p-val = 0.83)

there is also no effects of cancer status, with age and smoking in the model (p-val = 0.6355)

based on the model without the outlier, mutation doulbes every 48y, and smoker has 51% more mutations

There is no evidence that heavy smoker differ from moderate smokers in mutation rates

Change point model on pack-years among smokers

the effect of packyears flat above certain point

####################### Smokers only ###


dev0 <- -glm.nb(SNV_observed ~ Age + offset(log(surveyed_genome_adjusted)), data = SNV, 
    subset = Smoking_status == "Smoking")$twologlik
dev1 <- -glm.nb(SNV_observed ~ Age + Smoking_pack_year + offset(log(surveyed_genome_adjusted)), 
    data = SNV, subset = Smoking_status == "Smoking")$twologlik


### search for best change point

x <- SNV$Smoking_pack_year
dev <- c()
for (tau in seq(10, 116, 1)) {
    x.tau <- x
    x.tau[x > tau] <- tau
    glm.fit <- glm.nb(SNV_observed ~ Age + x.tau + offset(log(surveyed_genome_adjusted)), 
        data = SNV, subset = Smoking_status == "Smoking")
    dev <- c(dev, -glm.fit$twologlik)
}

### higher loglikelihood implies better fit

plot(dev)
abline(h = dev0)
abline(h = dev1)

glmer0 <- glmer.nb(SNV_observed ~ I(Age - 40) + offset(log(SNV_surveyed_genome * 
    SNV_sensitivity)) + (1 | Individual), data = mutations, subset = !is.element(Individual, 
    "Bulk1320"))

    SNV_sensitivity)) + (1 | Individual), data = mutations, subset = !is.element(Individual,

### search for the change point

x <- mutations$Smoking_pack_year
dev <- c()
for (tau in seq(10, 116, 1)) {
    x.tau <- x
    x.tau[x > tau] <- tau
    glmer1 <- glmer.nb(SNV_observed ~ I(Age - 40) + x.tau + offset(log(SNV_surveyed_genome * 
        SNV_sensitivity)) + (1 | Individual), data = mutations, subset = !is.element(Individual, 
        "Bulk1320"))
    dev <- c(dev, -2 * as.numeric(summary(glmer1)$logLik))
}

plot(dev)
abline(h = dev0)
abline(h = dev1)
abline(h = min(dev) + qchisq(0.95, 1), lty = 2)

### the best change point
tau.hat <- seq(10, 116, 1)[which.min(dev)]
tau.hat

    SNV_sensitivity)) + (1 | Individual), data = mutations, subset = !is.element(Individual, 
    "Bulk1320"))

dev2 <- -as.numeric(summary(glmer2)$logLik) * 2

1 - pchisq(dev1a - dev2, 1)
## [1] 0.1326556

With the outlier, we cannot find a sensible change point model

Without the outlier, and include all the subjects (smoker and non-smokers), we get a piece-wise linear model (flat after the change point) with the change point at 23 pack-years.

The model that is flat after the change point is statistically significantly better than the linear model (p-val = 0.0035), and the null model (p-val=0.00295). Furthermore, there is no statistical evidence that the slope is not zero after the change point (p-val=0.188).
